DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
    "PGstandard.pl", "MathObjects.pl", "PGML.pl", "parserPopUp.pl",
    "PGcourse.pl"
);

Context("Numeric")->noreduce('(-x)-y', '(-x)+y');
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0;

$m = list_random(-7, -5, -3, 3, 5, 7);
if ($m > 0) {
    $inc = "increasing";
    $dec = "decreasing";
    $pos = "positive";
} else {
    $inc = "decreasing";
    $dec = "increasing";
    $pos = "negative";
}
$popup    = PopUp([ "?", "increasing", "decreasing" ], "$inc");
$b        = non_zero_random(-8, 8, 2);
$g        = Compute("$b + $m x")->reduce();
$x1       = random(-4, -2, 1);
$x2       = random(3,  6,  1);
$y1       = $g->eval(x => $x1);
$y2       = $g->eval(x => $x2);
$dely     = "$y2 - $y1";
$delx     = "$x2 - $x1";
$compdely = Compute($dely);
$compdelx = Compute($delx);

BEGIN_PGML
a) What is the average rate of change of [` g(x) = [$g] `] between the points [` ([$x1], [$y1]) `] and [` ([$x2],[$y2]) `]?  
The average rate of change is [_]{$m}{5}.
b) The function [`g`] is [_]{$popup} on the interval [` [$x1] \leq x \leq [$x2] `].
END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a) If [`y = g(x)`] then between [` ([$x1] , [$y1]) `] and [` ([$x2] , [$y2] ) `],  
[``\hbox{average rate of change of }g =\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}= \frac{[$y2] - ([$y1])}{[$x2] -([$x1])}``] [`` =
\frac{[$dely]}{[$delx]}= \frac{[$compdely]}{[$compdelx]} = [$m].``]
b) Since the graph of [`g`] is a straight line, the average rate of change of [`g`] is constant.  By part (a), this constant average rate of change is equal to [`[$m]`], which is a [$pos] number.  Hence [` g `] is [$inc] on the given interval (and in fact over any interval).
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
